{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17506710","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17506710"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:46:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:46:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2560"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2560","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2560"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.31,0.23,0.11,0.25,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2560"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101923"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2560","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2560"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2560"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84380"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"385"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2628"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2646"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12569"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35430"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101923","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/101923"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old man is being reviewed by his general practitioner after two screening faecal occult blood tests (FOBT) were returned positive. He has never had any previous positive results, describes no changes in bowel habits but has recently noticed some blood on the toilet paper and describes no unintentional weight loss. He does not have any other health issues.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe is referred appropriately and consented for colonoscopy. He is found to have a 2 cm tumour at 30cm in his descending colon and biopsy confirms this as a moderately well differentiated adenocarcinoma of the colon. A staging CT does not show any evidence of local spread or distant metastatic disease.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Bowel resection","Neoadjuvant chemotherapy and resection","Neoadjuvant radiotherapy and resection","Bowel resection and adjuvant chemoradiotherapy","Neoadjuvant chemoradiotherapy and resection"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ETreatment will be determined by the staging of the disease:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EStage 0 - intramucosal disease\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EStage I - muscularis involvement\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EStage II - serosal involvement\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EStage III - adjacent lymph node involvement\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EStage IV - distant metastatic spread\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMore accurately, the TNM staging system will be used:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ET for primary tumor\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EN for lymph nodal involvement\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EM for metastasis\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAt this point in the patient\u0027s management it will be difficult to provide an accurate assessment of the degree of local invasion/spread of the primary tumour. He appears to have early stage disease. Whilst there are recent reports in the literature proposing the use of neoadjuvant chemotherapy for early stage colon cancer, the value of this strategy has yet to be proven and surgery with or without adjuvant chemotherapy should be maintained as the standard approach for these patients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThus the next step in the management of this patient should be \u003Cstrong\u003Ebowel resection,\u003C/strong\u003E which will be a left hemicolectomy. Following resection, a more accurate staging of the disease will be obtained from the histological analysis of the resected tumour and the adjacent tissues. The overall management of the patient should be discussed in a multidisciplinary meeting, where the surgical pathology can be reviewed and the TNM staging accurately assessed. A discussion can then be had on the possible role for adjuvant chemotherapy for this case. \u003Cstrong\u003EAdjuvant chemotherapy\u003C/strong\u003E is recommended for patients with Stage III colon cancer (those with regional lymph nodes positive), and those with high-risk stage 2 colon cancer (node negative cancers that have features such as deeper tissue invasion, high grade and perforation).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere is no role for \u003Cstrong\u003Eadjuvant radiotherapy\u003C/strong\u003E in the standard management of colon cancer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeoadjuvant chemotherapy\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Echemoradiotherapy\u003C/strong\u003E is increasingly becoming the standard of care for the management of locally advanced rectal cancer. However, this patient\u0027s tumour is clearly stated to be in the descending colon.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The first line of treatment for early stage colonic cancers is bowel resection."],"references":["Chan PC, Chapuis P. Selection of a clinicopathological staging system. Australia: Cancer Council Clinical Guidelines Network; 2017 Nov 7 [cited 2021 May 5]. Available from: https://wiki.cancer.org.au/australia/Guidelines:Colorectal_cancer/Adjuvant_therapy_for_stage_III_colon_cancer.","Luck A, Chow C, Farmer C, Hicks H. Optimal approach to elective resection for colon cancers. Australia: Cancer Council Clinical Guidelines Network; 2017 Nov 7 [cited 2021 May 5]. Available from: https://wiki.cancer.org.au/australia/Clinical_question:Surgical_resection_colon_cancer.","Audisio A, Fazio R, Dapra V, et al. Neoadjuvant chemotherapy for early-stage colon cancer. Cancer Treat Rev. 2024; 123:102676.","Vogel JD, Felder SI, Bhama R, et al. The American Society of Colon and Rectal Surgeons\nClinical Practice Guidelines for the Management of Colon Cancer. Dis Colon Rectum 2022; 65: 148\u201377."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84380"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2560"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84380","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/84380"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-05T15:07:40+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-05T15:08:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2560"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101923"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medic